<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="258" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1518,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,1518,1543]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male imago: 1) general coloration: thorax dark brown, abdomen black with anterior margins yellowish (
<figureCitation box="[159,283,1554,1579]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 2C, D</figureCitation>
) (see comments below in Thorax section about colour change with preservation); 2) hind wing with costal projection forming a right angle, located approximately 1/2 distance from base to apex of wing (
<figureCitation box="[1296,1423,1590,1615]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,229,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male imagos, wings. A–C) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov. A, forewing; B, hind wing; C, enlarged hind wing. D–F) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: D, forewing; E, hind wing; F, enlarged hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460074/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Figs. 3E–F</figureCitation>
); 3) terga I and IX completely black, terga II–VIII with basal yellowish bands, and tergum X yellowish; (
<figureCitation box="[1303,1393,1626,1651]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
); 4) penis projection spine-like of median size (approximately half of the total length of penis lobes) and medially directed (
<figureCitation box="[258,393,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1905,1927]" captionTargetBox="[179,1373,240,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1884]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male imagos, genitalia, ventral view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov. A, general aspect; B, penis, detail (ventral view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, general view; D, penis, detail." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460076/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Figs. 4C–D</figureCitation>
); 5) penis lobes fused on basal 1/3 (
<figureCitation box="[806,898,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1905,1927]" captionTargetBox="[179,1373,240,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1884]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male imagos, genitalia, ventral view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov. A, general aspect; B, penis, detail (ventral view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, general view; D, penis, detail." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460076/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
); 6) inner margins of lobes basally parallel and distally divergent, and outer margins strongly curved.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="259" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1518,2011]" box="[199,1056,1770,1795]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1770,1795]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Male imago.</emphasis>
Length: body: 
<quantity box="[518,607,1770,1795]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="6.2">6.2 mm</quantity>
; forewing: 
<quantity box="[735,824,1770,1795]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.1" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="6.1">6.1 mm</quantity>
; hind wing: 
<quantity box="[963,1052,1771,1795]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="258" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1518,2011]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,270,1806,1831]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Head.</emphasis>
Dorsal region dark brown; ventral region yellowish, with blackish marks. Upper portion of compound eyes reddish brown, lower portion black; ocelli whitish, surrounded by black (
<figureCitation box="[1074,1167,1842,1867]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Scape and pedicel of antenna brown, flagellum whitish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,1518,2011]" lastBlockId="6.[151,1437,151,1149]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="259" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,294,1914,1939]" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Thorax.</emphasis>
Pronotum brown, margins black; with a medial white mark. Mesonotum dark brown (in freshly killed specimens) as 
<figureCitation box="[320,409,1950,1975]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
to orangish (fixed specimens preserved for a long time) as 
<figureCitation box="[1104,1194,1950,1975]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="258">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
; longitudinal medial, anterolateral scutal, lateroparapsidal and medioparapsidal sutures light brown; posterior scutal protuberance, scuto- scutellar impression and scutellum black. Pleura brown washed with dark brown; membranous area yellowish. Metanotum dark brown. Sterna light brown, sutures darker. Wings membrane hyaline. Forewing with longitudinal veins whitish yellow and cross veins translucent; costal brace and base of veins C, Sc and anal section dark brown; fork of vein MP slightly asymmetric (
<figureCitation box="[575,666,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,229,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male imagos, wings. A–C) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov. A, forewing; B, hind wing; C, enlarged hind wing. D–F) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: D, forewing; E, hind wing; F, enlarged hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460074/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
). Hind wing with costal projection developed, forming a right angle, located approximately 1/2 distance from base to apex of wing; longitudinal and cross veins brown, except base of vein C to costal projection darker; costal region brownish, part of lower portion of hind wing dark brown (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1867,1889]" captionTargetBox="[179,1400,229,1784]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,193,1845]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 3. Male imagos, wings. A–C) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov. A, forewing; B, hind wing; C, enlarged hind wing. D–F) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: D, forewing; E, hind wing; F, enlarged hind wing." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460074/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Figs. 3E–F</figureCitation>
). Coxae and trochanters yellowish, washed with gray; femur orangish with blackish marks on apical region; tibia yellowish washed with black, apical region lighter; tarsi yellowish, tarsomeres I and II with apical blackish marks.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,323,476,501]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Abdomen.</emphasis>
Terga black with anterior margins yellowish. Terga I and IX completely black, tergum X completely yellowish, and terga II–VIII with basal yellowish bands (
<figureCitation box="[947,1041,511,536]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1891,1913]" captionTargetBox="[180,1396,381,1834]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,337,1869]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male imagos, general view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov.: A, lateral view; B, abdominal color pattern (dorsal view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, lateral view; D, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460072/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). Sterna yellowish. Genitalia (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1905,1927]" captionTargetBox="[179,1373,240,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1884]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male imagos, genitalia, ventral view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov. A, general aspect; B, penis, detail (ventral view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, general view; D, penis, detail." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460076/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). Styliger plate grayish. Forceps segment I black, apically lighter; segments II and III whitish gray. Segment II 0.11 the length of segment I, 1.58 the length of segment III. Penis lobes yellowish brown, fused on basal 1/3; each lobe rounded apically, separated by a distance either greater than width of one penis lobe, with a medially directed spine-like projection of median size (approximately half of the total length of penis lobes) projection; inner margins of penis lobes basally parallel and distal half divergent and outer margins strongly curved (
<figureCitation box="[1328,1422,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1905,1927]" captionTargetBox="[179,1373,240,1833]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,193,1884]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Male imagos, genitalia, ventral view. A–B) Simothraulopsis sinuosus sp. nov. A, general aspect; B, penis, detail (ventral view). C–D) Simothraulopsis gracilianus sp. nov.: C, general view; D, penis, detail." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1460076/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
); ventral region of penis lobes without a well-marked sclerotized region. Caudal filaments broken and lost.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="259" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,764,789]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Etymology.</emphasis>
Name in apposition, nominative singular from classical form. We are pleased to dedicate this species after Graciliano Ramos, a famous Brazilian modernist writer, politician and journalist that was born in the 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,837,861]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
