<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="259" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Lima, 2018" authorityName="Lima" authorityYear="2018" box="[342,659,980,1005]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gracilianus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[342,659,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">Simothraulopsis gracilianus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[667,757,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[667,757,980,1005]" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">sp. nov.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
has distinctive penis lobes in relation to the other species of the genus. The inner margins of penis lobes are basally parallel and divergent distally, and the outer margins are strongly curved. The apical spines are directed to the midline of the styliger plate as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mariano" authorityYear="2010" box="[1157,1357,1052,1077]" class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diamantinensis">
<emphasis box="[1157,1357,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. diamantinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Leptophlebiidae" genus="Simothraulopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="259" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eurybasis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="259">S. eurybasis</emphasis>
